Nobody really knew if the British plan to retake the islands was feasible. Nothing like that had been done since the Pacific campaign in WW2, it was still winter, supply lines were thousands of miles. Even with the Belgrano, no nuclear submarine had ever been used in anger, nobody on either side knew for certain whether huge capital ships like that were actually vulnerable.
It was an educated gamble by both sides. Turns out you can supply an aircraft carrier thousands of miles from base. Turns out you can maintain air superiority with sea harriers against land based jets that go faster. Turns out those big battleships have no defence against nuclear submarines.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rex_Hunt_(diplomat)

Sir Rex Masterman Hunt, CMG (29 June 1926 – 11 November 2012) was a British Government diplomat and colonial administrator. He was Governor, Commander-in-Chief, and Vice Admiral of the Falkland Islands (and concurrently High Commissioner of the British Antarctic Territory) between 1980 and September 1985. He became a household name in the United Kingdom during the Falklands War, after the Argentine invasion of the islands in 1982, when he was taken prisoner and temporarily removed from his position.

With the British forces facing overwhelming military and logistical odds, Hunt, after an extended exchange of small arms fire, with a handful of casualties, reluctantly gave the order to the Royal Marines to lay down their arms. He then went to Stanley Town Hall, wearing his full dress uniform, complete with medals, gold braid, neck ribbons, sword, sash and plumed cocked hat to face the Argentine invasion force's Commandant, Vice-Admiral Carlos Büsser, addressing him with: "You have landed unlawfully on British territory, and I order you to remove yourself and your troops forthwith". In response he was met with laughter, roughed up, his medals stolen and placed under confinement by the Argentines. Four hours later, under armed escort, he was flown out of the Falklands on a aeroplane to Montevideo, in Uruguay.[18] During the weeks of the war, Hunt stayed in London, while his wife and son were in a house in Kent.[19] He remained in this forced exile during the occupation of the Falkland Islands, until they were militarily liberated on 14 June 1982 by a British seaborne taskforce dispatched by the British Government, after which he returned again in full dress uniform and re-established its self-governance. Victorious British forces paraded past in review while he was clad in full dress uniform. He continued to serve in the post of its Governor until 1985.

Luca Brecel was at his brilliant best in the second semifinal on Saturday evening, turning on the style to claim his place alongside Selby in the final. Brecel’s lead proved too much, however, as he cruised over the line in the eighth frame.

I was looking at expansion options for the ACC, Big 12, and Pac-12 to get to 16 teams, since it seems like that's where we're heading.

ACC (14)
>UConn
Resources/facilities mostly in line with current members. NYC market. Stadium a bit small but respectable. Deepens your rich basketball tradition, ass at football.
>Temple
Philly market. NFL stadium (could be good or bad). Has been competitive occasionally.
>USF
3rd Florida team, but new market midway between FSU & Miami. NFL stadium but plans to build on-campus. Has been successful in past/can be again.
>ECU
Small market. Respectable stadium. Fairly successful G5.
>Liberty
Seems to have deep pockets for G5 (private, don't have to release finances). 3rd Virginia team. Small stadium. Very competitive in only 5 years in FBS.
>ODU
Decent-sized untapped market in Hampton Roads. Small stadium.
>JMU
Well-resourced for G5. Small stadium. Did well in first year in FBS.
>GA State
Have to imagine GA Tech would try to veto this.

BIG 12 (12)
>SMU
Natural fit as former SWC member. Small but passable stadium. Historic rivalry with TCU.
>Memphis
One of the most well-resourced and historically successful G5s. Decent-size market. Big stadium.
>UTSA
Very successful startup program on relatively small budget. Large market. World class domed stadium.
>USF
Could fit here if there was interest in reigniting rivalry with UCF.
>UNT
Geographic fit, lesser option than SMU/UTSA.
>Marshall
Relatively succesful without much in the way of resources. Smallish stadium. Historic rivalry with WVU.
>MWC school(s)
see: P12.

PAC-12 (10)
>SDSU
>Boise
>Fresno
As good as gone imo.
>UNLV
Ass program. City & stadium make them a serious candidate.
>UT State
>CO State
>UNR
>UNM
Take your pick. Not the greatest options but Pac-12 can't be picky. FWIW CSU has a slightly larger budget than the others. CSU and USU historic rivals of Colorado and Utah.
>San Jose State
Could be odd man out among MWC California schools. Very small budget. Small stadium.

Thoughts?
